'''Marilyn Puder-York''', PhD, is an American [[psychologist]], [[executive coach]], and author. A former staff psychologist for [[Citibank]], Puder-York applies clinical psychology in the field of executive coaching to help professionals achieve their optimal performance.

==Early life and education==
Puder-York has a PhD in [[clinical psychology]] from The [[Graduate Center, CUNY]] and a master’s degree in psychology from [[City University of New York]], and is a magna cum laude graduate of [[Brooklyn College]].{{cn|date=August 2016}}

==Career==
In her work as an executive coach, Puder-York focuses on one-to-one, organizationally-sponsored coaching for CEOs and senior executives in order to improve their leadership performance, career mobility, and direction.{{cn|date=August 2016}}

Puder-York works with executives to help maintain their resiliency during organizational and personal changes; adjust behaviors to fit the workplace; and identify and manage “blind spots” to help them achieve superior performance. Additionally, she consults with HR professionals to address behavioral issues in the workplace.{{cn|date=August 2016}}

In 2006, Puder-York wrote ''The Office Survival Guide: Surefire Techniques for Dealing With Challenging People and Situations'' ([[McGraw-Hill]], 2006),<ref>{{cite book|last=Puder-York|first=Marilyn|title=The Office Survival Guide: Surefire Techniques for Dealing With Challenging People and Situations|year=2006|publisher=McGraw-Hill|isbn=0071462031|url=http://www.amazon.com/Office-Survival-Guide-Marilyn-Puder-York/dp/0071462031|author2=Thompson, Andrea|accessdate=10 June 2013}}</ref> which advises on how to increase professional and personal resiliency in the face of challenges. The book aims to solve common problems (such as [[office politics]], [[passive-aggressive]] colleagues, corporate restructures, and mixed signals from superiors) to diffuse conflict, avoid negativity, and create a productive workplace.

As a public speaker, Puder-York addresses issues of resiliency, work and family, and coping with challenging bosses or professional situations.{{cn|date=August 2016}}

Puder-York served as Vice President and Director of [[Citicorp]]’s Global Employee Assistance Program for 10 years. In this role, she consulted Citicorp management and thousands of executives worldwide on mental health-related issues, and worked with senior management and HR to enhance employee efficacy and manage behavioral challenges in the workforce.

Puder-York is a former Staff Associate for the Legislative Office of Budget Review, where she was responsible for addressing mental health policy and budgetary issues in New York City. She has also served as co-founder and executive director of the East Village Girl’s Club, where she provided guidance and individual and group development services for girls living in the Lower East Side of [[Manhattan]].

Puder-York has been interviewed and cited in print and broadcast by the business and general media, including ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Nish|first=Caitlin|title=After an Office Gaffe, Several Ways to Say You’re Sorry|url=http://blogs.wsj.com/atwork/2012/12/17/after-an-office-gaffe-several-ways-to-say-youre-sorry/|accessdate=10 June 2013|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=December 17, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Garone|first=Elizabeth|title=What Should You Include in a Resignation Letter?|url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748704657304575540143127402012.html|accessdate=10 June 2013|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=October 13, 2010}}</ref> ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Reilly|first=Brian|title=Preparing for Leaner Times|url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1992/01/27/76011/index.htm|accessdate=10 June 2013|newspaper=Fortune|date=January 27, 1992}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=O'Reilly|first=Brian|title=Is Your Company Asking Too Much?|url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1990/03/12/73178/index.htm|accessdate=10 June 2013|newspaper=Fortune|date=March 12, 1990}}</ref>  ''[[Business Week]]'',<ref>{{cite news|title=Coffee Kinesiology|url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/2010-10-20/coffee-kinesiology|accessdate=10 June 2013|newspaper=Business Week|date=October 20, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Di Meglio|first=Francesca|title=When Cupid Visits B-School|url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/2005-02-11/when-cupid-visits-b-school|accessdate=10 June 2013|newspaper=Business Week|date=February 11, 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Mangi|first=Naween A.|title=The Aftermath|url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/2001-11-04/the-aftermath|accessdate=10 June 2013|newspaper=Business Week|date=November 4, 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gill|first=Jennifer|title=Work/Life: Groping for a New Balance|url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/2001-10-03/work-life-groping-for-a-new-balance|accessdate=10 June 2013|newspaper=Business Week|date=October 3, 2001}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Korkki|first=Phyllis|title=The Win-Win Way to Play Office Politics|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/16/jobs/16career.html?_r=1&|accessdate=10 June 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 14, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Villano|first=Matt|title=The Workplace: How to Cope with a Boss Who Meddles Too Much|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2006/05/30/business/worldbusiness/30iht-workcol31.1852020.html|accessdate=10 June 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 30, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Deutsch|first=Claudia H|title=Managing; Rankings by the Rank and File|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1990/11/18/business/managing-rankings-by-the-rank-and-file.html|accessdate=10 June 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 18, 1990}}</ref> ''[[U.S. News and World Report]]''<ref>{{cite news|last=Guerrero|first=Aaron|title=6 Tips for Dealing With a Passive Boss|url=http://money.usnews.com/money/careers/articles/2013/03/27/6-tips-for-dealing-with-a-passive-boss|accessdate=10 June 2013|newspaper=U.S. News and World Report|date=March 27, 2013}}</ref> and others.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jian Lee|first1=Deborah|title=6 Tips For Better Work-Life Balance|url=http://www.forbes.com/sites/deborahlee/2014/10/20/6-tips-for-better-work-life-balance/|accessdate=22 October 2014|publisher=Forbes|date=October 20, 2014}}</ref><ref name=HowToLearn>{{cite web|last=Puder-York|first=Marilyn|title=How to Create an Atmosphere for Problem Resolution|url=http://www.howtolearn.com/2012/01/how-to-create-an-atmosphere-for-problem-resolution|publisher=HowToLearn.com|accessdate=10 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Pollen|first=Stephen A.|title=How to Survive Getting Fired|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=M-MCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=legislative+office+of+budget+review+%22marilyn+puder-york%22&source=bl&ots=OOf1qmzKQV&sig=xHQ4d1jR4kf7Kpai9OU80bs8ZR8&hl=en&sa=X&ei=arWTUd3nJ9XJ4APih4CQAg&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=10 June 2013|newspaper=New York Magazine|date=September 7, 1992|author2=Mark Levine|pages=30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=West|first=Jennifer|title=Balancing Personal and Professional Life|url=http://issuu.com/amaalliance/docs/janfebtoday-final3|publisher=AMA Alliance Today|accessdate=10 June 2013|pages=6–7|date=Jan–Feb 2008}}</ref> She has appeared on [[CNN]], [[CBS]], [[NBC]] and [[FOX]] television networks.

Puder-York has written on topics such as leadership behavior,<ref>Puder-York, Marilyn (August 13, 2013). [http://www.cnn.com/2013/08/12/opinion/puder-york-aol-firing/index.html?hpt=hp_t4#! "AOL Boss Blew It In Public Firing"]. CNN.com. Retrieved 16 August 2013.</ref> ethical issues in executive coaching, managing difficult customers and clients, and the psychology of success for women.

She is a member of the [[American Psychological Association]], a Fellow of the [[New York Academy of Medicine]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Oliver|first=Kiri|title=2011 Annual Report|url=http://www.nyam.org/news/docs/AR_Final.pdf|publisher=The New York Academy of Medicine|accessdate=10 June 2013|pages=21}}</ref> and is a licensed clinical psychologist in New York State.{{cn|date=August 2016}}

==Personal life==
Puder-York is married to Christopher C. York, Esq. and has a daughter.{{Cn|date=August 2016}}

